The Evolution of Height in the NBA

Collaborators: Brian Diarra, Obinna Anako, Tyler Krauth, Jesuseyi Oyeyemi

Introduction

The National Basketball Association (NBA) is a men's professional basketball league in North America. It was founded in 1946, and since then has become one of the most popular sports leagues in the world. With millions of fans and followers, the NBA has produced some of the most iconic players in the history of the game. From the likes of Wilt Chamberlain to Shaquille O'Neal to LeBron James, the NBA has seen some of the greatest players of all time. One of the factors that have changed throughout the years in the NBA is the height of the players. In this tutorial, we will explore the evolution of height in the NBA, and how it has impacted the game.

Motivation

The main purpose of this project is to guide you through the entire pipeline of data science, focusing on the evolution of height in the NBA. Over the years, the game of basketball has evolved in many ways, with one notable aspect being the changing role of height in the sport. Tall players have gone from being primarily tough rebounders and shot blockers to exhibiting skills like shooting and playmaking, which were originally viewed as point guard and shooting guard specific skills, as seen in the rise of players like Victor Wembanyama. As height continues to play a significant role in the game, it's essential to understand its impact on the NBA landscape.

Why is this important? Analyzing the evolution of height in the NBA provides valuable insights into the changing dynamics of the sport. By understanding these changes, coaches, teams, and analysts can better adapt their strategies and develop more effective game plans. Moreover, such an analysis can also shed light on how the game has evolved in terms of athleticism and skill, ultimately enhancing the viewer experience for fans.

Throughout this tutorial, we will be going through the Data Science Lifecycle as follows:

  1. Data Collection
  2. Data Processing
  3. Exploratory Analysis & Data Visualization
  4. Model: Analysis, Hypothesis Testing, & ML
  5. Interpretation: Insight & Policy Decision

Data Collection

Data Collection Our first step in the data science life cycle is to search for a dataset that fits our topic. We need information on NBA players' heights, the years they played, and additional data that might be relevant, such as their positions and statistics.

The Kaggle platform, known for hosting a wide variety of datasets, provides us with an ideal source. We found a dataset named "NBA Players stats since 1950" at https://www.kaggle.com/drgilermo/nba-players-stats. This dataset is rich in detail and spans a good period, giving us enough data points to analyze the evolution of height in NBA players.

To download the dataset:

Visit the above link. Click on the “Download” button. Unzip the downloaded file and you will find three CSV files: player_data.csv, players.csv, and seasons_stats.csv. In this tutorial, we will be interested in all 3 files. Make sure to store the files file in your project directory.

During this project, we will be using the Python language, and we use tools such as IPython and Jupyter Notebook to develop this project. If you haven't heard about Jupyter notebooks before, make sure to learn more about them here.

To start any Python project, we need to import some libraries. Here are some of the libraries we will be using throughout this tutorial:

Data Transformation

In the code above, "player" is the existing column name and "name" is the new column name. After running this code, the column originally named "player" in the players DataFrame will be renamed to "name".

This was done to allow merge Merging datasets allows us to combine relevant data from different sources into a single dataframe that we can analyze. We used an inner join to merge our datasets, which means that only the rows with matching 'name' values in both dataframes are included in the output.

We also dropped certain columns from our dataset that were not relevant to our analysis. For instance,'height_y', 'weight_y' 'collage', '3PAr', 'ORB%', 'DRB%', and 'TS%' were dropped because they do not contribute to our analysis on player height:

We also converted the player height from inches to feet to make it more understandable:

Data Exploration

The first step in the data science pipeline is data exploration. This involves getting to know the dataset you are working with, identifying any missing values, outliers, and trends in the data. In your code, you begin by summarizing the data for the 2017 and 1973 seasons using the describe() function. This provides an overview of the central tendency, dispersion, and shape of the distribution of height data for each season. You then use a histogram to visualize the height distribution in each season. This helps to visualize the shape of the distribution, detect any skewness, and identify the presence of any outliers.
